## Modern Relevance and Future Trends – How Technology Is Trying (And Mostly Failing) To Fix It  

### Internal Talent Platforms and Marketplaces  

Digital platforms such as **internal talent marketplaces** ([Talent marketplace](/Talent_marketplace)) promise to streamline internal recruitment by using algorithms to match employees with openings based on skill graphs. In practice, the algorithms often reflect existing biases, resulting in a *mirror* of the old system—only now with more **data points** ([Data point](/Data_point)).  

[Skill graph](/Skill_graph)  
[Algorithmic bias](/Algorithmic_bias)  

### AI‑Driven Internal Mobility Matching  

Artificial intelligence is being marketed as the saviour that will *objectively* recommend the best internal candidate. Yet, AI models are only as unbiased as the data they are fed, and if that data is riddled with the same old favouritism, the AI will simply *reinforce* the status quo.  

[Machine learning](/Machine_learning)  
[Predictive analytics](/Predictive_analytics)  

### Remote Internal Recruitment and Virtual Onboarding  

The rise of **remote work** ([Remote work](/Remote_work)) has forced organisations to conduct internal recruitment entirely online. Virtual onboarding sessions now include *digital* introductions to the company culture, which, for many, feel as authentic as a **scripted** ([Scripted](/Scripted)) corporate video.  

[Virtual onboarding](/Virtual_onboarding)  
[Remote collaboration tools](/Remote_collaboration_tools)  

### The Future Outlook  

Looking ahead, internal recruitment will likely continue to be a *necessary evil*—a way for organisations to *save money* while *maintaining institutional knowledge*. However, unless companies are willing to confront the **ethical** ([Ethical](/Ethical)) and **equity** ([Equity](/Equity))) pitfalls head‑on, the practice will remain a sarcastic reminder that “the best person for the job” is often just “the person who already knows where the coffee is kept.”  

